<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the National Housing Federation</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">National Housing Federation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:14.18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Introduction and summary</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">We support the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">concept of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Universal Credit and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">potential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> ensur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> that people are better off in work by reducing benefit withdrawal rates. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">National Housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Federation has several concerns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">regarding the reforms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, primarily because households do not have a genuine choice to have the housing element of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">niversa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">l </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">redit paid directly to their landlord. Many tenants would elect to do this to avoid going into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. We are also concerned that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">cumulative impact of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">benefit cuts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">means that households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">increasingly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">cannot afford </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">cover the most basic costs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">feeding their family</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">keeping their home warm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> and paying their rent at the same time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Our response focuses on the case for abolishing the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Our recent ComRes poll shows that public opinion is shifting against the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">sec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">tor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">size criteria with 59% in support of Bedroom Tax repeal, up from 51% in April</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. In addition, 87% agree that those who need a spare room for sick or disabled family members should be exempt from the policy. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">We also outline a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">measures tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">t </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ould </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ensure the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">roll out of Universal Credit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">reduces the risk of tenants going into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">debt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">and protects social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">landlord</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">s’ revenue streams</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">To ensure we have information on the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> long-term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> impact of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">the Government’s welfare reforms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, the Federation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">commissioned Ipsos MORI to survey housing associations in autumn 2013 with a large scale tenants’ survey in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">early </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">2014. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">We would be happy to share the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">results with the Committee in due course. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">The best way to get </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">housing benefit bill down</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rise in the housing benefit bill</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in recent years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is a result of higher unemployment, stagnating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">low </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wages and rising rent levels in the private rented sector. The consequence is that, of every £1 of government expenditure on housing, 95p is spent on housin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g benefit and only 5p on building new homes</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Recommendation: the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">most effective way of redressing the balance and reducing the housing benefit bill is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">build more affordable homes. Government investment in new affordable homes not only helps tackl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">our growing housing crisis, but also has a fundamental role to play in:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">boosting the number of new homes across all sectors;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">economic growth;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">mproving employment mobility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:4.14pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">improving health outcomes and reducing health costs</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Impact o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">f welfare </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">reform o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">n rent arrears </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">and empty homes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">autumn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2012, 84% of housing associations believed that their rent arrears would increase </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a direct result of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">welfare changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (taking into account direct payments, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the social size criteria and the benefit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> cap)</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The average increase </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in arrears </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">expected was 51%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">At the end of 2012, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">housing association arrears stood at 5.1% (£572m)</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. If a 51% increase in arrears was realised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> across the sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, actual arrears levels would rise to 7.7% (totalling £865m).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This loss in revenue translates into a loss of financial capacity within housing associations to manage and maintain their properties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deliver wider community services and build new homes. If all these losses were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">diverted away from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">financing new homes, the country would see 17,480 less affordable homes built in a year. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouse b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uilding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may be more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">likely to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be felt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the next Spending Review period, as 61% of associations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">did not think welfare reform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ake it harder</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to deliver on their commitments under the existing Affordable Homes Programme</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Though 26% say it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a fair amount or great deal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The impact on tenants and communities would also be significant. For individual working-age tenants on housing be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nefit, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e predicted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would mean outstanding arrears increasing by £250 (up from £492) to £743 on average</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by year end</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Policis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, in a separate study for the Federation, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">found that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">50% of social housing tenants were not confident they would be able to keep up rental payments with a switch to monthly payments in arrears within a Universal Credit. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Policis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">identified </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">families with children, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">juggled their finances through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">weekl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y cash budgeting and were already under financial stress</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as most at risk in this move</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Policis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">found that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">32% of social housing tenants had problematic credit use and it was amongst this group that rent arrears were already concentrated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and risks to b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e foun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">3.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Recommendation: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">that households are given a genuine choice to have their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">housing element of Universal Credit </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; fon