n style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">s. O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">n other occasions new ones will need to be specified and fitted to match the design of the new home. In either scenario there are costs involved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> assessments by occupational therapists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> the labour for removing or fitting the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">aids and adaptatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">the costs of the equipment. Existing adaptations may become redundant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">it is not appropriate for them to be moved, or left for the incoming tenant. This represents a waste of historical investment and an environmental cost. The costs of re-providi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ng aids and adaptations represents an extra demand on the disabled facility grant (DFG) budgets of local authorities who have duties to assess the needs of disabled people and to meet the costs of appropriate facilities irrespective of their tenure</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">verage DFG award is £6,500</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">In turn, this puts pressure on central government which allocates funding to local authorities for DFG. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ousing associations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">aim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> to offer people a move to a home which has been built, or already adapted for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">needs. However, because of the limited supply of smaller properties this is far from possible in many cases. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">6.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The cost to the tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">y</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">er is not the only factor to consider. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Many households affected will find it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> difficult to find a suitable property to move to, or may face additional stresses in trying to co-ordinate moving with the successful and timely re-provision of aids and adaptions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Many will have to choose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">making up</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> the shortfall in their rent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> whi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ch would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">reduce their weekly household budget</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> moving to a less suitable property </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">which would put</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> limitations on going about their daily lives. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">6.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Government spokespeople repeatedly refer to DHPs as ameliorating the effect of changes to housing bene</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">fit, including the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">size criteria</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">uring the passage of the Welfare Reform Act, Lord Freud allocated an additional £30 million to DHP for 2013/14 because of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> aimed at disabled people living in significantly adapted properties and foster carers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">allocated an additional £35 million in year for 2013/14 to ameliorate the impact of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">part of a wider allocat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ion for 2013/14 which is now up to £190 million against allocations for previous years of £20m. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Though this falls well short of the £480 million savings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">in the first year </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">the DWP predicts tenants affected by the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">size criteria will make up in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">rental payments</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">, it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">is still an additional cost to the tax payer. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">an administrative error in the allocations to Scotland has resulted in the Government spending a further £800,000</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">6.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">It is entirely possible that the Government will continue to allocate further funds to the DHP </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">pot </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">impacts unfold</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. However, individual household</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> rely on DHP payments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">local authorities have to make very difficult decisions on how to ratio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">n their pot </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">over the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">across </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">properties owned by private landlords, local authorities and housing associations. Federation research shows that only 21% of local authority DHP awards from April 2013 to end of June 2013 were for six months or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">longer</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Does the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">size criteria meet its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">policy objectives?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Impact on savings</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">7.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The Government claims that the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">size criteria will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">save</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">the tax</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">payer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">£480 million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">in its first year</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Whether or not this is realised depends on the extent to which people downsize into the more expensive private rented sector and who subsequently moves into their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">vacated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">home. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Riverside, Affinity Sutton, Gentoo and Wigan and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Leigh Housing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> with support fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">om the Centre for Housing Policy University of York</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have run their own data through the DWP’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cost </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">impact model and this suggests that the savings may be considerably less than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ssumed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by the DWP. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Their modelling is based </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">observed level of moves </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by tenants affected by the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">size criteria into the private rented sector</span><a name="_ftnref24"></a><a href="#_ftn24">[24]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">Anal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">ysis from the Federation shows </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> families under-occupying two bedroom homes who move to a one-bed flat in the private rented sector would end up claiming an aver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">age of £1,500 more per year in housing benefit – even though they’ll be living in smaller properties</span><a name="_ftnref25"></a><a href="#_ftn25">[25]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">7.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The Government’s projected savings also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">fail to take into </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">account </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">subsequent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> costs to public services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">costs incurred by landlords </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">explored above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Impact on overcrowding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">best use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">stock</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">7.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">The social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">size criteria </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">is not a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">n effective</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> way of tackling overcrowding given the geographical mismatch between households who are under-occupying and high levels of overcrowding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">. It is also not a good way of making the best use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">affordable housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">stock </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">given the limited opportunities for people to move to smaller properties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal"> within the sector. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">For example, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">nalysis from the Federation shows: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.95pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orth of England </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">families with a spare room outnumber overcrowded families by three to one</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 37.95pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">there are 180,000 households under-occupying two bedroom social homes, but in 2011-12, only 85,000 one bedroom properties became available in the social housing sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and these ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e also in demand from people on the local authority waiting list</span><a name="_ftnref26"></a><a href="#_ftn26">[26]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">7.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">Recommendation: the Government should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">repeal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> the social </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">size criteria.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">http://www.housing.org.uk/media/press-releases/majority-of-public-believe-bedroom-tax-should-be-abandoned</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">PPR, Backing ‘benefits to bricks’: our big cities need deal-wheeling housing powers, May 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> National Housing Federation submission to the Spen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">ding Review 2015/16 available @ </span><a href="http://www.housing.org.uk"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt; font-weight:normal">www.housing.org.uk</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> Impact of Welfare Reform on housing associations-2012 baseline report for the National Housing Federation, Ipsos MORI and University of Cambridge, 2013 Ipsos MORI</span></